<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="1172" pageId="15" pageNumber="1171" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[160,1156,1471,1703]" box="[160,294,1471,1496]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1171">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,294,1471,1496]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="1171">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[160,1156,1471,1703]" lastBlockId="16.[160,1156,142,409]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="1172" pageId="15" pageNumber="1171">
Colonies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brewin" authorityYear="1946" box="[309,522,1506,1530]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polyclinidae" genus="Aplidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aplousobranchia" pageId="15" pageNumber="1171" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="benhami">
<emphasis box="[309,522,1506,1530]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="1171">Aplidium benhami</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected off wharf piles in Bluff Harbour are relatively large, compared to specimens sampled from natural substrata in more exposed environments. They are bright orange (5YR12), cushion-shaped, firm gelatinous colonies measuring up to 
<quantity box="[590,694,1610,1634]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="1171" unit="mm" value="100.0">100 mm</quantity>
in greatest diameter. The branchial apertures of the zooids are pigmented white, standing out against bright orange thoraces, and a lightly pigmented orange test (
<figureCitation box="[723,836,1679,1703]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="12.[160,225,1409,1432]" captionTargetBox="[163,1152,142,1378]" captionTargetId="figure-1@12.[163,1152,142,1378]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 6. In situ images of: (a) Diplosoma velatum (NIWA68092); (b) Polyclinum novaezealandiae (NIWA68097); (c) Synoicum stewartense (NIWA68089); (d) Aplidium benhami (NIWA68101); (e) Aplidium knoxi (NIWA68091); (f) Aplidium phortax (NIWA68109)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174620" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174620/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="1171">Figure 6d</figureCitation>
). Unlike the small colonies from other regions, the zooids are arranged in parallel rather than stellate systems, and common cloacal apertures are not obvious.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[160,1156,142,409]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172">
The zooids are stout, measuring 
<quantity box="[571,639,212,236]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
total length, with a thorax and abdomen of approximately equal length and a post-abdomen 
<quantity box="[720,784,246,270]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
long. The branchial aperture has low indistinct lobes, and the small atrial aperture is surmounted by 3 short atrial lappets. Three embryos are sequentially developed in the atrial brood pouch. The larval characters are as described in 
<bibRefCitation author="Page M &amp; Willis T &amp; Handley S" box="[460,660,350,374]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172" pagination="1653 - 1688" refId="ref9744" refString="Page M, Willis T, Handley S. 2014. The colonial ascidian fauna of Fiordland, New Zealand with a description of two new species. J Nat Hist. 48: 1653 - 1688." type="journal article" year="2014">Page et al. (2014)</bibRefCitation>
. Also noted in the present specimen is the orange pigmentation of the branchial sac.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="1172" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[160,1155,453,582]" box="[160,262,453,478]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,262,453,478]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[160,1155,453,582]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172">
The Tiwai Point 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brewin" authorityYear="1946" box="[350,478,489,513]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polyclinidae" genus="Aplidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aplousobranchia" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="benhami">
<emphasis box="[350,478,489,513]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172">A. benhami</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
colonies closely resemble the 
<collectingRegion box="[840,910,489,513]" country="New Zealand" name="Otago" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172">Otago</collectingRegion>
Harbour 
<typeStatus box="[1023,1123,489,513]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172">holotype</typeStatus>
in colour and zooid morphology (
<bibRefCitation author="Brewin BI" box="[508,649,524,548]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172" pagination="87 - 131" refId="ref8659" refString="Brewin BI. 1946. Ascidians in the vicinity of the Portobello Marine Biological Station, Otago Harbour. Trans Proc N Z Inst. 76: 87 - 131." type="journal article" year="1946">Brewin 1946</bibRefCitation>
). Furthermore, larval characters are the same for this species as described from Fiordland (
<bibRefCitation author="Page M &amp; Willis T &amp; Handley S" box="[673,858,558,582]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1172" pagination="1653 - 1688" refId="ref9744" refString="Page M, Willis T, Handley S. 2014. The colonial ascidian fauna of Fiordland, New Zealand with a description of two new species. J Nat Hist. 48: 1653 - 1688." type="journal article" year="2014">Page et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
